<sect2 id="file-pnm-export">
  <title>Export Image as PNM, PAM, PBM, PGM, PPM</title>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>Export Image as PNM</primary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Export Image as PAM</primary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Export Image as PBM</primary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Export Image as PGM</primary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Export Image as PPM</primary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Formats</primary>
    <secondary>pnm</secondary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Formats</primary>
    <secondary>pam</secondary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Formats</primary>
    <secondary>pbm</secondary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Formats</primary>
    <secondary>pgm</secondary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Formats</primary>
    <secondary>ppm</secondary>
  </indexterm>

  <sect3>
    <title>Overview</title>
    <anchor id="file-pam-export"/>
    <anchor id="file-pbm-export"/>
    <anchor id="file-pgm-export"/>
    <anchor id="file-ppm-export"/>

    <figure>
      <title>The PNM Export dialog</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="PNG"
            fileref="images/dialogs/export-pnm-dialog.png"/>
        </imageobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>

    <para>
      This export dialog allows you to export your image as one of the
      so-called <acronym>Portable Anymap</acronym> image formats. More
      specifically the PAM, PBM, PGM, PNM and PPM formats.
      For more information see
      <ulink url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netpbm">Netpbm</ulink>.
    </para>
    <para>
      Besides the above listed formats, there is also the related
      <link linkend="file-pfm-export">PFM</link> format.
    </para>
    <para>
      The formats can be used as follows:
    </para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>PAM</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This is an extended version of the below formats. This newer
            format allows for transparency.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>PBM</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This format saves the image as a monochrome bitmap with two colors:
            black and white.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>PGM</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This format saves the image as a grayscale image.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>PPM</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This format saves the images as a color RGB image without
            transparency.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>PNM</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            When using the generic name <quote>PNM</quote>,
            <acronym>GIMP</acronym> chooses the closest matching format
            from the above mentioned types.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>

  <sect3>
    <title>Options</title>

    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Data formatting</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This setting allows you to choose whether the image should be
            stored as <guilabel>ASCII</guilabel> or as <guilabel>RAW</guilabel>
            data. The former is a format that is easier to read by humans, but
            the latter, binary format, is more compact and results in
            smaller files.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>

</sect2>
